Printer Connectivity:

Local Connection: Direct connection to a computer using USB or parallel cables.

Network Printing: Printers connected via Ethernet or wireless antennas, allowing them to be shared across a home or office network.

Printer Sharing: A local printer can be shared over a network through a host computer, though the host must be powered on for others to print.

Types of Printers:

Inkjet Printers: The most common home printers . They work by moving a print head back and forth to place tiny ink dots on paper . They are affordable and produce photo-quality results, but the ink is prone to smudging

Laser Printers: Provide the highest quality prints but are the most expensive . They use an electrical charge on a rotating drum, which is then drawn on by a laser and coated with fine toner powder. Toner prints do not smudge .

Thermal Printers: Use heat to print on special thermal paper containing wax-based ink. They are very quiet and are typically used for printing labels and barcodes.

Dot Matrix Printers: Largely obsolete impact printers. They work by striking a cloth ink ribbon against paper with pins. While noisy and low-quality, they are very durable and capable of printing multi-copy carbon documents 
